  <exercise label="proofs-xe-7xe" adaptive="yes">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Arrange some of the statements below to form a correct proof of the following statement: <q>For any integer <m>n</m>, if <m>n</m> is even, then <m>7n</m> is even.</q>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <blocks>
      <block order="1">
        <p>
          Let <m>n</m> be an arbitrary integer, and assume <m>n</m> is even.
        </p>
      </block>
      <block order="2">
        <p>
          Since the product of any number with an even number is even,
        </p>
      </block>
      <block order="3">
        <p>
          <m>7n</m> must be even.
        </p>
      </block>
      <block correct="no">
        <p>
          Let <m>n</m> be an arbitrary integer, and assume <m>7n</m> is even.
        </p>
      </block>
      <block correct="no">
        <p>
          Let <m>n</m> be an arbitrary integer, and assume <m>7n</m> is odd.
        </p>
      </block>
      <block correct="no">
        <p>
          Since <m>7</m> is odd and the product of an odd number and an odd number is odd,
        </p>
      </block>
      <block correct="no">
        <p>
          Since an even number divided by <m>7</m> must be odd,
        </p>
      </block>
      <block correct="no">
        <p>
          <m>n</m> must be even.
        </p>
      </block>
      <block correct="no">
        <p>
          <m>7n</m> must be odd.
        </p>
      </block>
    </blocks>
  </exercise>
